    context: 'Social media platforms have fundamentally altered the way citizens consume and share political information. Where traditional journalism was filtered through editorial gatekeepers who verified facts and maintained professional standards, social media allows anyone to publish and amplify content without such checks. The result has been an explosion of information — and misinformation — that reaches audiences at unprecedented speed.\n\nResearchers have identified several mechanisms by which social media affects democratic participation. Algorithms designed to maximise engagement tend to promote emotionally charged content, which often reinforces existing beliefs rather than exposing users to alternative viewpoints. This phenomenon, frequently described as the "filter bubble" or "echo chamber" effect, can polarise public opinion and make constructive dialogue more difficult.\n\nAt the same time, social media has democratised access to political discourse. Movements that might once have struggled to gain visibility — from environmental activism to civil rights campaigns — have used platforms like Twitter and Instagram to organise, fundraise, and reach global audiences. The same tools that spread misinformation also enable grassroots democracy in ways that were previously impossible.',
